claude mem Phase 1 - Architecture Overview - Web
Claude-Mem is a hook-driven system layered on top of Claude Code’s CLI. Key components are: (1) Hook scripts run on lifecycle events (SessionStart, UserPromptSubmit, PostToolUse, Stop, SessionEnd) in the Claude Code session; (2) a background Worker service (in Bun) that asynchronously processes observations; (3) a local SQLite database (~/.claude-mem/claude-mem.db) storing sessions, observations, and summaries (with FTS5 indexing). Context flows as follows (→ denotes data/control flow):
[User in Claude CLI] 
    │ 
SessionStart hook → query recent sessions/observations → format an index/progressive-disclosure context → stdout → injected into new session context:contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}:contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}  
    │ 
UserPromptSubmit hook → create new session record in DB:contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}  
    │ 
Tool execution (Read/Edit/Grep/etc) → PostToolUse hook (save-hook) → enqueue observation in DB’s `observation_queue`:contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}  
    │ 
Worker service (HTTP API at port 37777) pulls from queue → sends to Claude Agent SDK for AI processing → parses XML response into structured “observation” records → inserts into SQLite tables (e.g. an `observations` table):contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}:contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}  
    │ 
Stop hook (summary-hook) at end of Claude’s response → gathers that session’s observations from DB → sends to Claude Agent SDK for summarization → parses summary into fields → inserts into `session_summaries` table:contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}:contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}  
    │ 
SessionEnd hook → mark session complete in DB (sets a `completed_at = NOW()` timestamp):contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}  
This architecture (hooks → worker → DB → injection) is summarized in the official docs and above.
Integration Points
Claude Code integration: Claude-Mem installs as a Claude Code plugin. It supplies hook scripts configured via the plugin’s hooks.json. Specifically, it uses SessionStart (twice, for context injection and setup message), UserPromptSubmit, PostToolUse, Stop, and SessionEnd hooks. For example, the PostToolUse hook runs on every tool execution (matcher="*") and invokes save-hook.js to enqueue an observation (non-blocking). The Stop hook invokes summary-hook.js to generate the session summary. The hook scripts communicate with the Worker via HTTP and the SQLite DB.
Shell/CLI: There is no special “file monitor” or external CLI wrapper beyond the Claude Code plugin. All integration is via Claude Code’s hook system. (For example, a pre-hook script smart-install.js runs at SessionStart to auto-install dependencies and start the worker.)
Memory storage: All memory (observations and summaries) is stored locally in a SQLite database under the user’s data directory (~/.claude-mem/claude-mem.db). Observations (tool uses, file reads/writes, etc.) and summaries are stored in relational tables (e.g. sdk_sessions, observations, session_summaries). Full-text search is enabled via SQLite’s FTS5 (for fast keyword search). Configuration (in settings.json in the same folder) controls limits: by default SessionStart injects context from the last 10 sessions and last 50 observations. Older observations beyond these limits are not injected (though they remain in the DB unless manually pruned). (No automated “rotation” beyond these limits is documented.)
Retrieval and reinjection: At each SessionStart, Claude-Mem queries the DB for recent context: typically it fetches the last N session summaries (e.g. 10) and the last M observations (e.g. 50) for the current project, then formats a timeline/index and writes it to stdout. This output is automatically included in Claude’s system prompt context. During the session, each new observation is simply enqueued and not immediately shown. At Stop (end of Claude’s response), a new summary is generated via the Agent SDK and saved to the DB. These summaries (and observations) thus serve as memory for future sessions. The official docs describe this injection logic in detail.
Implicit Assumptions and Lifecycle
Filesystem/OS: The plugin assumes a standard home directory (e.g. ~/.claude-mem) for data. It uses Node/Bun file I/O to create that directory and files (worked on Windows/macOS/Linux with Bun auto-install). No special network shares or unusual filesystems are assumed. Hooks run in the terminal environment of Claude Code, not a GUI.
Runtime/Timing: Hooks are non-blocking/fast (typically <1s). PostToolUse hook immediately enqueues each observation and returns without waiting for AI processing. The Stop hook does invoke the Agent SDK, which may take seconds, but it runs outside the main tool loop. The Worker service polls the observation queue (via HTTP API calls) or uses events to consume them asynchronously. Thus, reading from Claude and writing to memory happen on distinct timelines: tools trigger writes (DB inserts), and session starts trigger reads (DB queries).
Lifecycle: On session start (or after a /clear//compact), the SessionStart hook runs: it may perform a “smart install” (auto npm install) then runs context-hook.js to fetch context. During the session, each tool use triggers save-hook.js (PostToolUse) to enqueue an observation. When Claude finishes responding, the Stop hook runs summary-hook.js, which processes and stores a session summary. Finally, when the user ends the Claude Code session (SessionEnd), cleanup-hook.js marks the session as completed in the database.
Compaction/Pruning: There is no automatic pruning mentioned beyond the injection limits. The /clear command resets injected context but does not delete memory from the DB (it only closes out the previous session). No code indicates periodic compaction of stored memories; everything accumulates in SQLite unless the user manually deletes sessions.
Concurrency/Locking: Because Claude-Code hooks run in separate processes for each event, Claude-Mem serializes DB access via Bun’s SQLite. Each hook’s SQL insert is quick (<10ms) and safe. The docs explicitly note that PostToolUse enqueues in parallel without race conditions (“each hook gets own stdin”). No explicit file locking or mutex is visible in the code paths (SQLite itself handles multi-access). No buffer overflows or native memory issues are evident; data from Claude passes through JSON/XML.
Determinism
Entry Ordering: Observations and summaries are time-stamped upon creation (e.g. the save-hook attaches a created_at_epoch timestamp; the cleanup-hook sets session end NOW()). Thus, order of entries in the DB is by insertion time. In the absence of external randomness, the chronological order is stable. However, if two tools fire rapidly, their insertion order may vary by milliseconds (the system does not serialize them beyond timestamp).
ID Generation: Session and summary IDs are generated by the DB (likely auto-increment PKs) or use Claude’s session ID. For example, the cleanup-hook uses SET completed_at = NOW(), embedding wall-clock time in each session record. This means IDs and timestamps are not reproducible across runs. Two identical sessions on different days will have different completed_at and thus different internal IDs.
Non-deterministic outputs: The summaries themselves are generated by Claude (via the Agent SDK), so they may vary slightly even for the same observations (LLM outputs can be non-deterministic). Also, context injection depends on “recent sessions” and “recent observations” which may change if new entries occur, so identical user prompts in two separate runs might yield different injected context if the memory DB state differs.
Security and Privacy
Redaction/Private tags: Claude-Mem provides a way to exclude content from memory: any text wrapped in <private>...</private> is not saved to the database. This relies on hook scripts stripping or ignoring <private> spans. (No other automatic redaction is performed.)
Data flow trust: All memory comes from the local user’s Claude sessions. The SQLite DB is local-only (no network calls). The docs explicitly note that user prompts and observations are stored only in local SQLite (not sent to any cloud). This forms the trust boundary: untrusted input to Claude (e.g. copying secrets into the CLI) could end up in the DB unless wrapped in <private> tags. Conversely, memory is only reinjected into the same user’s sessions.
Risk of secret ingestion: If the user inadvertently includes sensitive data (passwords, keys) in a tool input/output without marking it private, Claude-Mem will store it in plaintext in the DB. There is no automatic scanning for credentials, so this risk is mitigated only by the <private> mechanism and user caution (as noted by the developer in docs).
Claims lacking direct code references are marked UNKNOWN. For example, we cannot confirm any built-in encryption of the DB (likely none), nor hidden traps or buffer issues without inspecting the TS code. All above behaviors are documented or implied by the hook architecture and configuration scripts.
